description: PUH-BrianMartell Planck Cores in PUH v25 carry enormous internal currents (~10^{16} A range for neutron-star mass cores) from braided torsional twist. These currents are not static — the core “breathes” or precesses as lattice tension relaxes and rebuilds. Fluctuations in current produce a low-frequency magnetic “hum” — the Heartbeat of the core. Simple picture: •  Core twist ξ oscillates around equilibrium (breathing mode). •  Current I ∝ ξ (twist density). •  Magnetic moment μ ∝ I × area → oscillating dipole. •  Frequency f_heartbeat ≈ natural torsional mode ~1 / (core size / v_ripple) scaled to lattice stiffness. •  For neutron-star mass core (~10 km), f ~ mHz to μHz range — detectable with ultra-sensitive magnetometers. This hum is the direct signature of living Planck Cores.
